<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>The core representation renders the core idea of a representation.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>The intention of representation is indicated by core representations and by citation from other representations.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>The representation that has a direct link to the core representation is close-core representation.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>The core representation of a scientific paper is rendered by its keywords, title, abstract and conclusion.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Representations linked to the close-core representations are relevant-to-core representation.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>For scientific papers, a core representation reflects motivation, problem or solution.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>A core representation has a high rank in the citation network.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>The intention of representation p is indicated by (1) the core of p, Core(p), consisting of the core representations of p;</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>Other representations are peripheral representations.</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>The intention of a representation is rendered by commonsense, which is indicated by the basic representations.</a>
<a name="10">[10]</a> <a href="#10" id=10>A core representation takes the priority of emerging when reading.</a>
<a name="11">[11]</a> <a href="#11" id=11>A representation can be composed by a set of representations.</a>
<a name="12">[12]</a> <a href="#12" id=12>A good article renders just one core.</a>
<a name="13">[13]</a> <a href="#13" id=13>Citations form the intention and extension of a representation.</a>
<a name="14">[14]</a> <a href="#14" id=14>Citation is a kind of representation by individual selection and language use.</a>
<a name="15">[15]</a> <a href="#15" id=15>Generally, citation is a kind of representation of selection and language use.</a>
<a name="16">[16]</a> <a href="#16" id=16>The extension of representation A consists of all representations that cite A and are cited by A.</a>
<a name="17">[17]</a> <a href="#17" id=17>Citation is the basic element of a scientific paper.</a>
<a name="18">[18]</a> <a href="#18" id=18>Therefore, a representation p can be formalized as a structure of representations:</a>
<a name="19">[19]</a> <a href="#19" id=19>In scientific papers, the core representations usually appear in the front and in the end (e.g., title, abstract and conclusion) so that readers can be impressed before and after reading the main body.</a>
